,Recommended,255710,17743477,"Posted: 27 August, 2015",all,frodo2397,"In short, the best game in its genre to date. BUY IT!There's no way an ordinary schmuck is going to write a review to top Mayor Todd's, so, instead of the usual review that compares this game directly to similar games, here is a list of some fun things you can do in this game:1) Play offline, with a smooth framerate and a sensible interface2) Build beautiful, sprawling 3D cities (rather than 2D grids or absurdist skyscraper hamlets), and view them with a few different color palettes3) Get Steam achievements4) Follow individual cars, trucks, buses, trains, and airplanes fromrealisticorigin point torealisticdestination5) Micromanage public transportation, as in OpenTTD (which is free, btw.)6) Build or downloadawesomehighway interchanges, with ramps, bridges, and tunnels (like the double-paperclip interchange)7) Watch as trucks pile up in one lane of a six-lane road, causing fury and hair-tearing on your part(this is one of the few cons)8) Build ultra-modernist, utopian phalansteries that would make Le Corbusier proud9) Build facsimiles of older, Southern European cities (using ""European-style"" maps)10) Join the urban farming movement, only to watch your semi-realistic gravel roads get clogged with absurd numbers of tractors11) Cause disease due to sewage contamination, floods that disable buildings, and floods of contaminated sewage that causes disease and disables buildings, thanks to improper water management (water physics in this game are somewhat believable)12) Build a surfeit of fire stations, incinerators, and crematoria (or watch your people suffer)13) Build  OP monuments that give massive amounts of electricity, universal (cheap) health care, universal (cheap) education, huge land value increases, and other crazy benefits, after torturing your city to meet arbitrary/sadistic production requirements (e.g., health care satisfaction under 20%)14) See a whole bunch of generic Scandinavian buildings and vehicles that kind of look like they came from a kid's train set15) Speaking of train sets, this game lets you set up digital dioramas involving trains and transportation, and view them with Simcity 2013-style tilt shift shader (don't worry, you can turn it off if you don't like it)16) Make your own maps and interchanges using the built-in tools (or decorate existing buildings)17) Rename people, houses, businesses, and districts (or, for that matter, abuse eminent domain) to get the perfect ""feel""18) Make your own hiking trails and place trees manually along them for aesthetics19) Build huge, attractive residential zones, only to find that, forty years later, all the people there get old and die, thus overburdening your deathcare system, which spreads disease, which causes more death, which causes economic collapse, which causes industries to fail, which causes commercial zones to whine about not having goods or customers, which causes power outages when you bulldoze the commercial zones, which cause all the remaining citizens to pack up and leave.20) Spend 100 hours straight building one city, and forget about your family, your school, your job, and your overheating graphics card (until the game crashes and you lose your city... NOOOOOOOOOOOO!!!!)Here is a list of things you can do in this game with Workshop content and mods:1) Play offline, sometimes with a choppier framerate2) Build even more beautiful cities, using EVEN MORE SPACE, and view them with a variety of different shader effects (such as ambient occlusion, edge detection à la Borderlands, ""godrays,"" and Dynamic Resolution)3) NOT get Steam achievements (unless you install another mod)4) Follow individual vehicles with a first-person view--and, for a greater challenge, reduce their speeds to make for realistic traffic congestion levels5) Micromanage public transportation a bit more (including dedicated bus roads, bypass passenger stations, public parking garages...)6) Build even better highway interchanges, with better lane controls (seriously, I've spent hours doing this)7) No mods to fix this one yet, though some help mitigate it8) Build post-modernist tract housing (à la suburban America), brutalist slums/housing projects, British row houses, and trailer parks (or ""caravan clubs,"" for you Brits out there)9) Build insane skyscrapers that tower unrealistically over pieds-a-terre and hipster-infested coffee shops, and then surround them with statues of evil hamsters and giant blobs of metal10) Make farms that kind of look like farms11) Cause tsunamis and massive floods12) This one's still a problem; why can't one or two crematoria be enough?!13) Build community-designed monuments that may, or may not, be overpowered14) Download tons of vehicles and growable buildings from the Workshop (from Coca-Cola trucks to Winnebago RV's toFallout-esque shanties, complete with Nuka-Cola machines), and spice up your roads15) Did I mention thatrealistic historical locomotivesare available on the Steam Workshop?16) Make buildings, mods, etc., and upload to Steam Workshop (for more adventurous types)17) Clone growable buildings to get the perfect aesthetic (believe me, this is cooler than it sounds)--or, better yet, place individual props yourself18) Make your own hiking trails, place trees with Tree Brush, and hike the aforementioned trails19) Do that, but without the incessant Chirpy tweets of ""#movingout.""20) Spend 150 hours building your city; run into 65,536 object limit in game after getting to a population over 200,000... NOOOOOOOOOO!!!!""Cannot place any more objects of this type.""Must... build... more... stuff...""Cannot place any more objects of this type.""Must... build... more... stuff...TL;DR (99% of people say so after reading this review) BUY IT! BUY IT! BUY IT!"
