,Recommended,255710,25747613,"Posted: 28 September, 2016",all,A Glowing Thing,"Cities: Skylines is without a doubt the best city builder/simulator to date. Just imagine all of the other city builders/simulators you've played now combine the best parts and you get this, plus more.What I liked:User Interface- All of the menus and tooltips are very polished and very legible. Extremely easy to use. Simple in overall design, it won't overwelm you.Great Population Simulation- The simulation is very percise especially when it comes to street traffic. It also exists litterally its not just numbers/math in the background. You can see and track whats occurring in the simulation, The combined functions of health, education, police, etc work extremely well and effect the population with the most realisism in the genre. Funding litterally affects performance by limiting say a hospitals actual resources less ambulances, less beds, less doctors has effects that you can really see in the whole simulation. Traffic effects the performance of all elements the use roads. As resources are litterally transported in vehicles and the longer it takes for them to get there stops functionailty of other systems.Well Balanced Population Needs- The creation and coverage of services/leisure correctly influence the land value and allow the population to upgrade its businesses and homes in a detailed and sensible fashion.Excellent Power and Water Grid Simulation- When not enough water/electricity is being generated the furtherest structures based on the distance of connections through other building and powerlines/pipes are the building effected by it. Meaning that the grid actually exists rather then just being production minus requirement.Procedural Appearance/Connections- There is no grid that strictly defines where structures and roads are built. Instead you can draw curved roads that have correct appearances. Building built on curves will connect visually to the nearby structures and roads accurately. Intersections and changes to road types merge well.Policies- you can have global policies and specific policies. You can mark your own custom areas for the specific policies. Many of the policies actually have useful effects that also are shown in the overall simulation.Information Views- Selecting a service in the menus or specifically activating the contextual informative view has a complete full 3-D and statistcal analysis that is easy to understand.Dynamic WeatherTerraforming- The tools for changing the ground itself are also easy to use and the terrain has a very detailed mesh so hills, etc look very smooth.Water Physics - The water bodies actually feature flowing water. Terraforming and Canals will manipulate water flow. You can flood your city. This is also import when it comes to building dams as water has a rate of flow based on the terrain its flowing through.City Specializations- Resources are fully simulated. As in they are not extracted for a single purpose/objective. Normal industry actually needs the materials to function. Industry will either import resources from outside of your city or get it from within your city. Resources can only be found in certain areas in the map or not at all. When you create industry zones over a resource they will need to be specilized using the policy zones. When you've picked say agriculture the industry zones will become farms. The farms performance depends on the quality of the area. The normal industry and commercial structures will use generated resources. If you produce more than your city needs the goods will be exported out of the city.Continuing Development- The game is being expanded upon through dlc paid content and some free patches. Getting seasons gameplay is a paid dlc while the canals and terraforming were added for free. The paid dlc adds seasons, new Night related simulations with new commercial options, and a new public transportation option. The free patches added; road conditions and servicing, dynamic weather, terraforming and canals, stadiums, custom themes and other specific buildings. Do remember if we want to see more in the game they can't do the work for free.Mod Support- Mods are fully supported allowing quite substantial changes. Some could be considered cheating, but for the most part many of them are graphical changes and upgrades. The most useful Mods that are not cheating are very helpful. Things like deeper traffic analysis and tracking, Manual road Intersection options, custom road speed limits, protractors for drawing roads, along with many others. Many of the things missing from the vanilla game can be found as mods as well as nicer graphics to change up the look of things.Things I disliked:Engine Bottleneck- Eventually you will have such a large city that the simulation will become to much to process. Observing the hardware however the engine is making full use of the processor.  Your maximum city size without taking a performance hit is determined by your processor bottlenecking if you don't have a good one, but eventually you will start losing performance regardless.Performance/Graphics- The graphics are okay, but when you start getting a lot of structures in your city. The graphics card usage gets unreasonably high for what you get. Your maximum city size without taking a performance hit is determined by when your graphics card bottlenecks. The default appearance of the game colour wise is very dull. Theme mods get you past this.Broken Tourism- After Dark has rendered tourism useless and even without After Dark seems to have very little useful functionality. This has been the case for quite a while now.Final Summary:The developers are releasing patches to optimize the engine along with new features. Optimization aside you will still find the game very playable. Even with broken tourism its still a lot better then the competitors in its current state. I'm sure you won't regret supporting the games further additions and fixes if you pick it up today.(I will remove or change the negatives if they are resolved)"
