,Recommended,255710,33151831,Posted: 2 July,all,IDescribedEternity,"City: Skylines brings me the oh so nostalgic feelings that came when I played Sim City 4 and knowing how well acclaimed that game is, I can certainly say the same for City: Skylines. I have only made 2 cities without any of the offical DLC and with very limited usage of mods, particularly the zoom in mod and ploppables.This game is pretty great for me because I certainly like my eye candy and just the IRL day by day progress you can put into a town of your own creation just makes my day after work. With the zoom mod, you can certainly create some photgenic scenes so if you're a screenshot hussy, go cray. Gameplay wise: for the most part you just zone and plop when you get pass the intial stages which can be tricky but the rest is pretty easy, mechanics-wise. It's certainly no easy feat however to make a gorgeous city like you see all those celebrity Youtubers out there and I may say that it might be nigh impossible to do so without pre-planning, at least from my experience. I like to think that it's that indirect part of the City: Skylines that makes the game so many city builder vets love; that is not only making the city but experimenting with certain styles and going off in a tangent as to what you'll conceive in order to make your city truly a sight to behold. Just as a brief, it's like Sim City 4 with the hold information overlays, the plopping of services and problems that plague a city however I do like the architecture, the art style and more diverse line-up of ploppables that came with Sim City 4 but City: Skylines has it's own realism niche going on so it's hard to compare aside from the avaliablity of ploppables in certain in-game categories.The issues that existed in Sim City 4 still exist in City: Skylines which are entirely subjective and people don't make much note of it but by Jove, I hate it when you're zoning in apparently flat land or even on a slope and your zoned building come out as craggly unrealistic floop that certaintly just become eye candy from a far. SureI could flat it out but it just seems very time consuming though whether there's a solution to this, I do not know. Flattening land on a hill also seems redundant as you want the hill to stay a hill and I wish they could simulate that in a more realistic manner if possible. More leisurely ploppables like a zoo, radio station, military base, the fair and of course, the mayor's manor in the vanilla game would be nice but just minor irks that very few are likely to express.Best citybuilder out there, good for babby's first game because of the overall easy difficulty of the game but also a good city planner simulator if you have the patience to do that which I don't but just to have it as a considerable option is nice, especially at the price you can snag at for, It's almost a steal with how much it goes on during sales. One thing to note, I have a 1 year old laptop and this game runs at 15 - 20 fps so, as much as I want to play more of it, my own personal technical experiences limits the experience of course this is no fault of the game.Buy it. 10/10 because I'm not a picky prissy."
