76561198026913459,Recommended,255710,14884695,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,troublmaker,"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Jsz7aafGvhwCities: Skylines is not the perfect city management simulator.  There are so many things I want to do that I cannot do.However, it is probably the best one on the market currently as it allows you to do the most.  The game brings a lot of innovative concepts to the table that we just have to wonder why no one else thought about it first.Much like every city builder you zone areas for residential, commercial, and industrial areas.  Then people come and build them.  After you progress so far in the game you will unlock the urban zones, urban residential, urban commercial, and office zoning.Once you have a population they will have demands.  The most basic demands are electricity and water.  In order to get water you need to build the pipeline that will connect all the water to the people.  To add a degree of extra care you will also need to pump out the dirty water back into a body of water.  If your poop flows down to your water source you will be feeding people poopy water.One of the big problems with city builders is that they quickly transform into traffic simulators.... which is perfect for CO because that's what Cities in Motion was all about.  All the services you place has to be used around the city meaning they have to be able to get to places.The game comes with built in infrastructure to handle that.  Highways make for 100KPH speedways to get across the city.  Traffic circles can be used in place of four way intersections to allow for a free flow of traffic.  Turnpikes and cloverleafs can be placed down to allow people to enter and exit a highway freely.  And then you have all your standard fun tools like 1, 2 and 3 lane roads, 2, 4, and 6 lane one way streets.The game is a bit preachy on environment, but I guess you have to expect them for a Euro developer.  As you city expands you will have to buy up new plots of land which means more opportunity to pollute.The preachiness comes from an in-game simulation of Twitter.  Every now and then people will tweet to you their concerns using various viral hashtags like #healthcareFTW or #masterrace.  All environmental reforms are universally applauded, while destroying jobs is seemingly never a problem.And there's the big problem.  You can play the game 100% without building industrial spaces.  It's the same old problem with SimCity.  There is a deterrent in which you wil have to buy industrial goods for your commercial zones which means no taxes from commercial zones.  But it's 100% playable without industrial zones.That's not to say it's easy.  The start of the game has absolutely no tax revenues and you have to be able to plot out your city before your money runs dry.  After that it is several hours of being unable to afford services like fire protection and ambulances until you finally enter an urban city which is far easier to manage.The game isn't perfect, but it is the best city builder on the market.  It's cheap and given this studios track record we can expect a tonne of DLC development as well as post-launch balancing."
,Recommended,255710,27404528,"Posted: 25 November, 2016",all,Julez_,"Wow, Cities: Skylines... Where to begin...- Firstly, this game is the game that EA's Simcity should have been, except about 1000 times better. More buildings, more options, better gameplay mechanics and generally more everything!- Secondly, The gameplay and the customisation feature of this game are truely its strong point. With thousands of Workshop items, assets and vechicles created by a community of dedicated fans that are added to your game with a simple click. This adds a whole new level to a game which no other rival city builder can truely compare to. Did I mention that these Workshop add-ons are FREE???- Thirdly, The Developers ACTUALLY CARE ABOUT THE GAME. That is one thing that EA missed on with Simcity, EA just rode the current of their popularity river that the Sim series has created and as soon as the game was released, the game was mostly left to cough, splutter and die due to its lack of new features, AI problems and repetitiveness. Simcity did see a few updates but nothing compared to the love this game has recieved from the developers.This game has problems though, it has to be said. I have experienced problems during my play time, mainly around the stability on my PC, especially seeing as I am not running your typical /r/pcmasterrace beast machine. Asides from the occational lapse of framerate, crashes can occur. In the past, I have been left with a few hours of progress wiped because of foolishly not saving my progress. Collosial Order seem to have fixed this as crashes seem to happen less frequently then it used to but I do still see a occasional drop of FPS in my game, but again, I am not running an epic PC. Thinking of it, this game is so addicting that I have had to force myself to save or enable autosave.But that's really it, a lot of pros and a few tiny cons. Cities: Skylines is a must have for gamers who like Simulation games, City Builders, Moddable games and a whole lot of mircomanaging.EDIT (25/11/'16): I highly recommend buying the game with the extra DLCs. Although it will set you back a bit more, you will be supporting future development of the game and the extra features are mostly worth it. Think of it as a virtual highfive to the devs."
76561198032600860,Recommended,255710,14829766,"Posted: 10 March, 2015",all,Soloeus,"About time we have a good City Builder from a reputed company.After playing this for some time, here are some feedback compared to SimCity4: Deluxe.PRO:1. Game starts as expected. Build some roads, electric, water, and zones.  Bulldozing gives money back instead of costing money.You don't spend money to zone or re-zone.  You can easily lose if you screw up this part. A second failure point that can crop up at this stage is placing something now that creates a pollution hub later.2. There is a lot to manage but you start small - then as you get bigger, the more you need to manage. Progression feels good and appropriate for a game in this genre. Pacing is also smooth. The Pace is dictated by Milestones, as you reach certain goals in the game you get to purchase more land, unlock buildings and more upgrades.3.  Mods in this game are pretty good in their potential.  Anyone can make Assets or Maps.4. There is enough to simulate to entertain you but there isn't too much depth.  The level of depth feels appropriate.  Not dumbed down by any means.5. Lots of potential room for DLC, Expansions and more content WITHOUT being stripped down to nothing.  This is not a half-game awaiting the rest in microtransactions.CON: No big flaws yet.1. Some parts of the UI are primitive.  When you click to view Energy, Waste, Fire or Crime, it doesn't tell you how much money you are spending on it. So there is some juggling of one tab to the next.2. You cannot move or re-size the windows that open for you when you click buttons.3. The music could have a better presence.  It is a bit quiet and often I hear nothing but birds.4. ""Forced"" to start small and build big from scratch.  You ""can cheat"" if you like, but playing without cheats you cannot just start building a large city. Some people might dislike having the same starting situation evey single time on terms of what you can build and how you advance.Linear Progression is the rule of this Sandbox.  Fortunately, you can advance in a non-linear way.Overall:  9/10.  The only thing that could have made this game better is to have more control over the size of Zones - the ""Zones"" appear next to road types when you build roads. You don't place ""zones."" Once the road is placed and the ""Zone Spot"" appears next to the road, you may designate that as Residential, Commercial or Industial.This is the best City Builder on the market, period."
