76561197998902443,Recommended,255710,30458195,Posted: 11 March,all,danielk,"Best city builder ever, particularly for those who also enjoy traffic management games. This game simulates everything all the way down to single citizens! For example, how well a particular junction design works is not hard-coded (indeed, you can and should draw your own interchanges), but emerges from the simulation of all the moving parts. Check out highway engineering designs on Wikipedia and build them in the game -- it works and is great fun!The modding capabilities as well as the available mods are absolutely great. I have about 20 mods installed and wouldn't want to miss one of them. In particular, Network Extension Project and Traffic Manager President Edition are must-haves.The game is regularly updated in parallel with new DLC releases, which generally add nice features and fun new stuff to play with. The Natural Disasters DLC in particular turned out to be much better than I expected: Whereas in classic SimCity games disasters were something you only turned to when fed up with the game, Cities: Skylines actually gives you the means to respond to disasters constructively, making it an integral part of the gameplay.Some notes on system requirements: The game runs well on both Linux and Windows, with about the same hardware requirements on either. I mainly play on Linux, without any issues. However: To fully enjoy this game, you will likely need more than 8 GiB of RAM (I upgraded to 16 GiB just for this). Also, four CPU cores are needed to run larger cities at full speed. As to graphics, a mid-level GPU should do fine (GTX 950 works for me).Conclusion: Thoroughly enjoyable game and well worth the money!"
