,Recommended,255710,14958872,"Posted: 19 March, 2015",all,SisterFister,"I'm sure everyone's saying it but it's true: Cities Skylines is what Simcity 2013 should have been.I could go into detail to explain how the game plays but it's pretty much just like Simcity 2013, just without always-online DRM, multiplayer and half-baked traffic and agent mechanics (Skylines still uses agents for traffic and sims, but not for things like electricity and water, which frees up resources to have a lot more sims on the streets without fudging population figures. Every single population point is an actual sim which actually has a proper home, car, etc., unlike Simcity 2013 where sims just ran to the closest house, shop or job in some kind of pitiful game of Musical Chairs). You can even give sims names (hell you can give animals names as well), though good luck finding them again with all the other sims running around. And the base price for Cities Skylines is also about half that of Simcity 2013 as well.And while Cities Skylines initially starts you out with city limits roughly the same size as a Simcity 2013 map, you can later purchase up to 8 additional adjacent sqaures so you can end up with a city 9x the size of anything you could build in Simcity 2013 (and there are already mods which allow you to unlock a total of 25 squares, which is crazy and will probably bring all but the most beefy of rigs to their knees).Colossal Order's only other titles to date have been Cities in Motion 1 & 2 (which are traffic simulators rather than actual city builders) but they have really gone all out with Cities Skylines. You can tell that they have experience with traffic simulations (which is important given how traffic is such an integral part of city builders, especially agent-based ones). They have also pledged to support the game with free and paid updates for years to come (with possible expansion packs). They have said that one of their first free updates will be one that introduces the ability to build underground roads and tunnels, for example.Colossal Order have already released a patch within the first week addressing a few issues that people had (for instance it introduces the ability to disable the Film Grain graphical effect, allows you to now upgrade between one and two-way roads and right-click one-way roads to change their direction which are both significant quality of life enhancements, and addresses a few other bugs and balance issues like parks decreasing Commercial demand). Oh and of course the game is completely offline (there's not even a multiplayer mode to speak of, which frankly is the way it should be) and the game has extensive mod support via the Steam Workshop (unlike a certain other city builder..)The game has a few nagging problems but nothing that makes me sit back and think 'yeah stuff this, back to Simcity 4', and that's an achievement in my books. My only real gripe is with the Chirper notification tool. It can get a little repetitive seeing citizens constantly tweting the same few inane things when you'd rather just hear about any actual problems in your city (even then it seems that for most problems or events there's only about two types of messages you get from Chirper - one positive and one negative, if that. For instance, if you have a district dedicated to oil industry you'll constantly get messages that either say something along the lines of 'oil pumps look bad, why can't we import oil from.. wherever it comes from' or 'good thinking using the oil beneath our city', and that's it. Basically there's no variety in the messages and they just keep complaining to you or praising you until the end of time, when you'd rather more meaningful feedback.I don't normally bother to recommend games but in this case I have to make an exception. It takes a lot these days for a game to actually impress me to the point of writing up a review for it. Honestly the only thing I legitimately hate about Cities Skylines is that it reminds me of just how much better Simcity 2013 could have been and that I actually forked out money for that pile of crap. Keep in mind that Colossal Order are rather small compared to the Simcity team.If you're a fan of city builders like Simcity and similar games you're doing yourself a great disservice by not at least taking a good hard look at Cities Skylines.One could almost say that creating a city builder that could not only stand up to Simcity but legitimately topple it is a.. Colossal Order ~snicker~"
