,Recommended,255710,18338823,"Posted: 5 October, 2015",all,Luciforged,"So freakin' addictive. It's like the days of Simcity 3 all over again.Building plans and road layouts have to make sense, traffic is very realistic and will build up and drive to and from destinations. Have to create special roadways for heavy cargo to make traffic flow like a beating heart. I've never been a mayor but how you play this game, really makes sense in how you would actually run a village/town/city in real life. 50% of my citizens have a college degree, and they DO NOT want to be underemployed lol I found this out after I noticed my population started to drastically decline when I got to about 24,000 people. But you will have to find a good balance, not eveyone is going to want to college, so you will need good high paying highschool education or lower jobs. It's satisfying to find out why a zoned area is having a problem and then turn it into a bright part of the community. Interestingly enough, it's a very simple concept. Treat people like human beings and they will work hard, have ambitions, and in return give the city more money in the form of taxes to help improve said city. Every citizen is going to want to feel safe, have a local hospital staffed by local people close by with honest doctors, not worry about their house family and belongings being burnt up in a fire, Keeping their houses tidy by keeping garbage out of the streets. For instance, the laws have a invest now-risk/reward later effect. Sign a law that encourages people to recycle to help produce less garbage which will keep your garbage dumps clean while you wait to get approval to build garbage powerplants to burn the excess garbage. You'll get slightly less tax income, but you won't have to spend as much as quickly mantaining more and more garbage dumps. I love this game. I wish there were more extreme policies that could only be approved if you met certain conditions like for example- cime is 8%, I can now unlock an outreach program policy that would further reduce crime. I LOVE that they made a policy just to ""legalize it"", I signed that bill as soon as I could, and then turned around and banned ciggerettes. In my mind, I do not trust cigarettes because of the extra chemicals they include with tobacco, so I wasn't actually banning smoking tobacco, just big corporate ciggerettes; my citizens, seemed to approve, health in general went up 5% and oddly enough so did happiness. It did dip 2% for a few weeks, then rose about 5%. For a small gain of 3% I hope they continue to make dlc for this game, it has so MUCH potential and it's already my city management game of choice as of this review."
