,Recommended,255710,14845193,"Posted: 11 March, 2015",all,InTheGhett0,"A quality city-builder though not as Messianic as some make it out to be.Graphcis are solid, but not stunning.Mechanics are a harmonious blend of detailed and easy-to-use.TL;DR below.This game borrows from previous city-builders which had success, namely SimCiy 4 and Cities in Motion, while avoiding the pitfalls which made Cities XL and Simcity 5 disasters.In the end, this game's appeal is greatly heightened by the disappointments of Simcity 5 and Cities XL and it's ""Sequels"" which looked frightening like clones of their predecessors.While innovative and clever (especially with way pollution directly impacts the game environment via the soil and the water), Cities:Skylines innovates only mildly while maintaining an overall pleasant experience.The graphical experience does come off a bit fuzzy despite settings being maxed and the game is sorely in need of an update which establishes a day/night cycle. A solid game with excellent gameplay. Easy to grasp, semi-tough to master, this game is as solid 8/10 with the potential to become a 9 - 9.5 with a high definitions texture upgrade and a few feature upgrades (smog effects, clouds, weather, day/night cycle to name a few.)While it scratches an itch long unscratched given that SimCity 4 is 10 years old and there have been no legitimate challengers to it's dominance save a disappointing Cities XL experience, Cities is a good that could be great but seems to be a few steps away from being genuinely terrific.TL;DR8 / 10 with the Potential to be better with a few solid updates that will (hopefully) not end up as cash grab DLCs.A good buy at $20 or less, but unless you are desperately in need for a city-builder, I wouldn't pay full price for it.Fun, easy to get into and enjoyable, though a bit fuzzy graphically and asking for an HD upgrade."
