76561198054906218,Recommended,255710,21321798,"Posted: 19 February, 2016",all,Yr Mom,"This game is straight-up addicting. I was a little worried when I bought it, that it would one of those games where you get lost in the micro-management and numbers-crunching and if you don't keep every detail perfect, then everything goes to hell.But in fact, playing Cities: Skyline is straight-forward, stream-lined and actually pretty easy. You don't have to build individual buildings - just zone an area, and the buildings will sprout automatically. If your citizens are unhappy, it's easy to find out what's wrong. Dragging roads, water lines, and establishing zones has a very intuitive feel. There's a solid, steady pace to the game: you're not inundated with responsibilities, instead, they gradually accumulate as your population expands.The tutorial is sorely lacking, so for the first 30 minutes I was thoroughly confused - that was aggravating. But C:S shows you all the information you need to know with the overlays and information panels, so it's not difficult to find out what to do."
