,Recommended,255710,21238386,"Posted: 15 February, 2016",all,¥ung_Salad,"Were you excited for SimCity 2013? Were you then promptly disappointed with SimCity 2013? Then get excited for Cities: Skylines, but leave out the ♥♥♥♥♥♥ disappointed part.Quick Summary: Cities: Skylines aspires to be everything SimCity promised to be. Highly customizable, moddable, large scale...the list goes on. For the most part Cities exceeds at everything it aimed to do, and at a great price point. If you love making your Cities, and not having to think about worrisome volcanoes rising from the ground and alien invasions destroying your city, Cities: Skylines may just be the perfect city simulator for you.Positives:-EASY TO MOD. This is by far the best part of this game. The community is active in developing important/essential mods to improve gameplay and interactivity. There are also built in asset tools, which means you can boot up the game and make your own building or map and upload it to the workshop or just use it for yourself!-Active developers, that are adding new content every couple of months through paid DLC. Although if you do not want to pay for DLC, non-paying players will still get some of the features from the DLC.-LARGE SCALE CITIES! Yes, you can have a city with 1,000,000 people in it. Or you can have a small village of only 500. It's up to you! Cities gives you tons of space to experiment with. 9 tiles max in unmodded gameplay, which adds up to 6x6km, or with a mod you can get up to 10x10km. Much larger than SimCity provided.-Great price for what you get. At $30 dollars base and $12 or so per DLC this game comes out to be an amazing deal for the potentially endless city building entertainment you get.Downsides:-EASY TO MOD. It's a double edged sword...there are many basic flaws in the game (no easy public transportation management panel, no built in day/night changer, no in game terraforming tool etc.) that the developers have seemingly passed off to the modders to deal with. None of these issues are huge, but it is certainly sad to see, considering the massive potential of this game.-No modular buildings (except for modded buildings which can be finnicky). Lets say you have a school in SimCity, and you are over capacity. Simply add another wing to the school! In Cities, the buildings are not able to be added on to in a modular fashion. Not a huge gripe, but a downside none the less.-No real difficulty curve. While there is a hardcore mode, which enables huge death waves, plagues and city-wide fires, Cities is extremely easy to manage once you have a hang of the basics. In survival it is normal to see massive reserves of cash that the player will never really end up digging into.-Seemingly uncurable city collapses. So, this contradicts the last downside to an extent. This can be a game-breaking bug which causes your city to catch the plague and never return to it's healthy self. This is a RARE bug, and I have only had it happen once out of my 15-20 cities, but there is evidence that it has happened to others. This is more of a heads up than a true downside.Overview: Cities: Skylines is the best city simulation game on the market right now. It's ability to be modded in any which way, and with such ease, makes it easy to customize your gameplay exactly how you like it. Whether it's building an insane city with roads going straight up and through eachother, or building your perfectly designed metropolis, there's always something on the workshop that will catch your eye and your imagination. The community is what made Cities the amazing and endless sandbox that it is today, and that is what will continue to make it an amazing game into the future. If you love making pretty stuff, and not having to worry about the bully on the playground ruining your sandcastle, then Cities should be a no-brainer for you."
