76561198032073091,Recommended,255710,14953937,"Posted: 18 March, 2015",all,imaphilosopher,"10/10In my opinion, this is the PERFECT city building game -- the one I've been waiting for since I first played SimCity2000, oh so many years ago.  This game does what the new SimCity (on Origin) SHOULD have done, and tried (but miserably failed) to do.  For me, Cities: Skylines takes the cake as the best city-builder.Cities: Skylines allows the player to start from nothing, and grow one tiny neighborhood into an ultimately sprawling, fully integrated and interconnected network of high density cities and lower density towns.  You start with one (farily large) square of territory, then build up a nice bustling village, and gradually expand your city by purchasing other, directly-connected squares of territory with new resources and topographic features, until you have a realistic-feeling region.  (This feature contrasts greatly with the new SimCity, which only technically allows you to expand into a ""region,"" since it really only allows you to focus on one square of territory at any one time.  Cities: Skylines gives you a full view of your expanded territory, you can build in any part of your territory at any time, and you can see that your various smaller cities are all a part of a larger interrelated region.)  This ability to gradually expand into a true, interconnected megalopolis, and the additionalability to create smaller districts (neighborhoods), and set policies that are specific to each one, are some of the game's best features.  The game allows you to have real control over what happens in each area of your region.The road and transportation system is also quite intuitive, and generally allows for easy manipulation and changes.  Transportation systems are easy to set up and change (unlike in SimCity), and I feel like there is a good amount of freedom in setting up roads.  I only wish you could easily change a two-lane road into a one-way road, which it doesn't seem to allow you to do.  But that's a minor critique of an otherwise STELLAR game.I will say that the game sometimes runs a little choppily on my crappy (but new) Acer laptop, and the graphics are a little fuzzy, but I am positive that this is the result of my aforementioned crappy machine, and not the result of any programming flaws.  Also, the imperfection of the graphics on my machine does not lessen the value of the game for me.  In my opinion, this game satisfies all the requirements for a perfect, ever-engaging city-builder.  The replay value is amazing.  I have put in 45 hours of playtime in about two weeks (by starting and expanding three different cities), and I know I've still  barely scratched the surface.  I can't wait to see how my cities progress!!If you enjoy the city-building genre, then BUY THIS GAME NOW!!!  Take it from someone who's played just about every city-building game that's been released in the past 25 years - Cities: Skylines will make a worthy addition to your collection.10/10; 5 Stars; A+++"
,Recommended,255710,14838863,"Posted: 11 March, 2015",all,Krogsager,"So, Cities: Skylines.. I was probably a bit late to the party, but it quickly caught my eye!Haven't played too much so far, and still haven't figured it all out, but it's awesome so far! :D"
,Recommended,255710,14841021,"Posted: 11 March, 2015",all,Gamer Guy Steve,"If you, like me, have been hoping for someone to get the City Builder genere right in a modern game, then the product you have been looking for has arrived.   You start with a plot of land equal in size to the city plots in Sim City (2013), but don't scream in frustration, that's just the beginning.   As your city grows, you can buy more of these plots of land, each one the same size as the first.  These unlocks start coming realtively early (the first one is at a mere 500 citizens), and continue to come along as your city grows.   Most of the time, you wll find you are able to acquire new plots of land far before you actually need them.   There may be some exceptions to this if you are starting in an area with a limited amount of buildable land.   In total, you can unlock up to 8 of these lots (in addition to the one you started with), so what you end up is a city 9x the size of the cities you can create in Sim City (2013).   Still not enough?  While you can choose to unlock up to 9 tiles, the map itself is actually 25 titles in a 5x5 grid.   There are already mods out for the game that will allow you to unlock all 25 tiles.   Bear in mind, that the 9 title limit was put in place by developer to keep performance up.  If you decide to use a mod to unlock more and your game suffers from performance issues, it's not the fault of the game, it's the fault of using it in a way that the developers specifically advise against.So let's talk about performance shall we?   While the game is quite lovely to look at, it's not highly demanding from a graphics standpoint, at least certainly not by today's standards.   While a better graphics card may allow the game to look nicer, it's not going to have a large impact on performance.   The bulk of the work is done by the CPU and not the GPU.   Every single sim (including pets and wild animals) are fully simulated AND PERSISTENT.   Unlike Sim City (2013), this simulation is not an illusion, it's real.  The citizens of your cities go to the same job every day (unless they get a new one), go back to the same house every day, have the same family, etc.   They grow from children to teens to adults to young adults to elders.  Whether they went to elementary school, high school, or university matters.Even the water in Cities Skylines is fully simulated.  It has mass, volume, velocity, etc, all which play a role if you start building dams as a source of electricity.   The stronger the current, the more electricity you will be able to produce.  Of course, if you place the dam in the wrong spot, you could end up flooding part (or even all) of your city.  You have to make sure you are carefully considering the location of your dams before building them.     Learning how to do this can involve a bit of trial and error, but the results aren't random, so once you learn what to look out for you can better estimate the optimum position for a dam.If there is anything negative I have seen so far (and I use the term lightly because this is really not an issue), it is that there only a few maps that you can choose to start with and you can't choose your starting plot on that map.  It will always be the same.   None of the available maps are based on any real world locations and are simply generic maps created by the developers.   This is completely nullified by the fact that the game includes an extensive map editor and created maps can easily be uploaded to the Steam Workshop where installing them for use is as simple as clikcing on the ""Subscribe"" button for the map(s) you want to try out.While the startup screen provides the option of logging into a Paradox Interactive account, this is not required in order to play the game.  Cities : Skylines is 100% offline with no current plans for multiplayer functionality (at least not from the developers).Population numbers can seem a little low in Cities : Skylines compared to other city builders, but there is a reason for this.  The population number you see is actually the number of citizens being fully simulated (as described above).  They population numbers in Cities : Skylines aren't artififially padded to make a city seem larger than it is.   The absolute maximum population you can reach in a city is one million.   While that may seem low, it's quite impressive since that means you are running one million simulations.      You really can't compare population numbers across city builders anyway because the number is usually artbitrarily calculated and has no real meaning outside of that indvidual game.   It's like scoring an impressive 40 points in a basketball game and being upset about it because you scored 300 points in gin rummy the week before.With a price tag of just under $30, this game is well worth the investment.   You'll be getting your money's worth and a whole lot more.   Other games ask for twice as much and don't give you near the amount of sheer enjoyable gameplay."
